LEGIONELLOSIS - AUSTRALIA: (VICTORIA)
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 18 Aug 2021 5:58 PM AEST
Source: news.com.au [edited]
https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/legionnaires-disease-outbreak-investigated-in-melbournes-south-east/news-story/eeee3d8ffb74d78bbde69147557700cf


An outbreak of legionnaires' disease is being investigated in Melbourne's south east after the discovery of 2 cases. The Victorian health department is investigating after 2 cases who live in the Cranbourne East area were reported to authorities on Wednesday [17 Aug 2021]. Both required hospital treatment.

Local cooling towers, pools, and spas are being tested to find the source of the outbreak.

Those who have been in the Cranbourne East area from the start of August [2021] and develop a flu-like illness are being urged to seek immediate medical attention.

Legionnaires' disease is caused by _Legionella_ bacteria, which are widespread in the environment, in natural water bodies such as rivers, lakes, creeks, and hot springs. The bacteria are also found in spas, potting mix, warm water systems, and artificial systems that use water for cooling, heating, or industrial processes, such as cooling towers. People can catch it by breathing in fine droplets of water that contain the bacteria. It cannot be caught from another person or by drinking contaminated water.

Acting deputy chief health officer (Communicable Disease) Dr Mihaela Ivan urged health care professionals on Wednesday [18 Aug 2021] to be on alert for legionnaires' disease in patients with influenza-like symptoms, particularly those with severe pneumonia who've been around the Cranbourne East area since the start of August [2021]. The disease often presents with initial influenza-like symptoms such as myalgia, headache, fever, and cough, and may progress to atypical pneumonia, sometimes with confusion. Those at great risk include those aged over 65, smokers, heavy drinkers, those with chronic lung disease and underlying conditions such as diabetes, cancer, or kidney failure.

Doctors are also being urged to consider alternative diagnoses to COVID-19 for respiratory infections and undertake appropriate investigations. Legionnaires' disease is an urgent notifiable condition, meaning it must be reported to the health department upon initial diagnosis or clinical suspicion as soon as possible and within 24 hours.

There is no vaccine to prevent the disease, but early diagnosis and treatment with appropriate antibiotics can reduce the severity of illness and complications.

[Byline: Melissa Iaria]

