Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Humans acquire legionnaires' disease after exposure to natural or human-made aquatic reservoirs, usually by means of inhalation of aerosolized _Legionella_ bacteria, but the disease can also be acquired by aspiration of _Legionella_-contaminated potable water in people prone to aspirate, such as debilitated hospitalized patients. Possible person-to-person transmission of legionnaires' disease has also been described (Correia AM, Ferreira JS, Borges V, et al. Probable person-to-person transmission of legionnaires' disease. N Engl J Med. 2016; 374: 497-8; http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMc1505356). _Legionella_ infection can be acquired less commonly by contamination of wounds.

More than 70 percent of cases of legionnaires' disease are due to _L. pneumophila_ serogroup 1, except in Australia and New Zealand, where _L. pneumophila_ serogroup 1 has accounted for only 45.7 percent of cases of community-acquired legionellosis and 30.4 percent are _L. longbeachae_ (Yu VL, Plouffe JF, Pastoris MC, et al. Distribution of _Legionella_ species and serogroups isolated by culture in patients with sporadic community-acquired legionellosis: an international collaborative survey. J Infect Dis. 2002; 186(1): 127-8; https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/186/1/127/837207).

Legionnaires' disease due to _L. longbeachae_ is associated with exposure to aerosols generated during the use of non-sterilized potting soil, which apparently contains free-living amoebae and elevated storage temperatures may foster the intra-amoebic growth of _L. longbeachae_ in the potting soil (Ross IS, Mee BJ, Riley TV. _Legionella longbeachae_ in Western Australian potting mix. Med J Aust 1997; 166(7): 387; https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.5694/j.1326-5377.1997.tb123175.x).

A cluster of cases usually refers to multiple cases in space and time that are possibly linked. An outbreak of legionnaires' disease implies a common source is suspected (https://legionnaires.ecdc.europa.eu/?pid=205). Culture for _Legionella_ in sputum and suspected environmental sources and genotyping the isolates will help delineate transmission pathways. A common source is suggested if the genotype of _Legionella_ isolated from patient specimens match; genotyping environmental isolates of _Legionella_ can point to the possible source for those patients if the environmental and patient genotypes match. However, if the diagnosis of legionnaires' disease in the 2 patients was based only on a positive urinary antigen assay, there will be no isolates for genotyping.

A previous outbreak of legionnaires' disease in Cranbourne, a suburb 43 km (26.7 mi) southeast of Melbourne's central business district, was suspected to have originated from cooling towers near a shopping center (see ProMED post Legionellosis - Australia (02): (VI, SA) 20170513.5034030). Cranbourne East, where the current cases reside, is 3.5 km east of Cranbourne. A map showing the location of Cranbourne East can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Cranbourne+East,+Victoria+3977,+Australia/Cranbourne,+Victoria+3977,+Australia.

Melbourne, with a population of about 4.6 million residents, is the capital and most populous city in the Australian state of Victoria, and the 2nd-most populous city in Australia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melbourne). Maps of Australia can be seen at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/images/oceania/australia-political-map.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8605989,68517. A map of Melbourne can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Melbourne+VIC,+Australia. - Mod.ML]
